reviewText: I agree with one of the other reviews that this is more syfy schlock. But it did have several elements I like in my schlock. There is always a sociopathic authority figure that doesn't value human life with a counter-agenda. As these movies "plot" (if you can call it that) unrolls, I start hoping that by the end of the movie, the "hate-ables" will get what is coming to them. By about three quarters of the way through the film, I had decided who I was hoping would be eaten by the end. Sometimes it is ok to root for the monster. I do feel bad for Stella, who didn't ask to play this particular role. I am not sorry I watched it. I don't even mind that I paid several dollars.This movie was a combination of "mutant species" and any of the syfy croc movies.http://www.amazon.com/Mutant-Species-Powers-Boothe/dp/B009TR448Y/ref=sr_1_3?s=instant-video&ie;=UTF8&qid;=1394713857&sr;=1-3&keywords;=mutant+species

Title: Robocroc

reviewText: I live in a world where two things are certain: (1) the SyFy network will continue to pump out spectacularly bad movies and (2) strange creature hybrids are here to stay. For the record, I love me some bad movie mayhem and look forward to many of these diabolically awful monster movies. But there is a fine line between campy badness that makes everything good and just plain badness. "Robocroc," in the pantheon of similar SyFy films, has relatively little to distinguish it from the pack and, therefore, stands as a rather bland example of just plain badness! Think about it: we've had Mega Piranha, Mega Shark, Giant Octopus, Sharktopus, Crocosaurus, Mega Python, Dinocroc, and Gatoroid to name just a few beasties (and sadly, each of these creatures is burned into my memory!). This Robocroc just isn't that compelling in relationship to some of the more lunatic creations. But beyond the uninspired central creature, "RoboCroc" simply isn't fun enough or silly enough to make me recommend it. With a leaden pace and non-existent plotting, I was ready to shut it down after about 30 minutes. I kept hoping it would take a delightfully demented turn, but it never got wacky enough to become a true guilty pleasure.It's unfortunate, really, because the movie stars one of my favorite actors on the SyFy roster--Corin Nemec. Nemec has made a career of being in these preposterous movies and I applaud his committed performances even in the most diabolically bad movie! Here, though, not even he could salvage this unimaginative mess. The crocodile at the heart of "RoboCroc" is the outcome of a military experiment gone awry. The toothsome creature has been infected with cybernetic robotics that have turned it into a unstoppable killing machine. OK, I'm down with that premise. It's absolutely ridiculous and I love it. But when the creature starts to rampage in the zoo (with an adjacent lake and water park), it is up to a brash zoologist (Nemec) to lead a heroic charge. He is alternately aided by and thwarted by the efforts of his staff, the military, and a scientist (Dee Wallace) with an agenda of her own.The primary plot revolves around the crocodile's (named Stella) proximity to Adventure Cove. As the movie progresses, we spend a lot of time with characters that you don't care about doing rather silly things at the water park. Nemec's son is at the park (of course) which adds a personal drama that wastes too much time. The overall production is rather drab and the effects are lackluster even by SyFy standards. Nemec and Steven Hartley (as the military man in charge) give it a go, and Wallace is deliciously over-the-top. But they can't compensate for the relentlessly dull pacing. The movie follows every formula you've come to expect from these things, and doesn't have much fun with its own lunatic premise. I'll say it, this movie simply bored me. You've seen it all before and you've seen it better. By all means, check out "RoboCroc" for free on SyFy when it airs again. But it's not a movie I can imagine you'll watch more than once which makes it a difficult DVD recommendation. In the end, I don't mind that "RoboCroc" was bad, I simply wanted it to be fun as well. KGHarris, 2/14.
summary: In The World Of Bad Movie Mayhem: This Techno-Croc Lacks The Bite Of Some Nuttier And More Fun Creations

reviewerName: The Movie Guy "Movies from A to Z"
reviewText: The military loses a bunch of nano-bots in a zoo where they immediately fly into a crocodile and turn it into a mechanical killer, with an appetite for jailbait in bikinis. Duffy (Corin Nemec- saved the planet also in Dracano) is the knowledgeable zoo keeper and croc wrestler. He is joined by a biologist (Lisa McAllister who played "passenger" in "Dark Knight)  who just hired on. In spite of that fact she has nice eyes and he is capable of developing deep feelings for her in about 45 minutes after they show each other their scars. The film is saved by the evil one, Dee Wallace. Dee as you recalled personally rescued 1 star films like "Bonnie & Clyde: Justified," "Hansel & Gretel" "Lords of Salem" and "Exit Humanity." I look forward to seeing her star as Sharon Sommers  in the much awaited release of  "Zombie Killers: Elephant's Graveyard."I think you get the picture. Not much to see here except the same old stuff. $9.96 Walmart. They rolled the credits real fast at the end, apparently no one wanted to be be known they were connected to the film. The small print on the back is a bit blurry too.Parental Guide: No F-bombs, sex, or nudity. A film you let the kids watch before you go to the zoo.
